      <h2>The Core Difference</h2>
      <p>A harmonium is specifically designed for Indian music: it produces the warm sustained reed tone that complements Indian singing, has a limited range that encourages mastery within that range, and its mechanics (bellows pumping) develop a physical connection to sustained musical breath. An electronic keyboard is versatile covers many styles and often includes learning features but lacks the authentic tone and physical connection of harmonium.</p>

      <h2>Choose Harmonium If</h2>
      <p>You want to accompany Indian classical singing or bhajans. You plan to lead or participate in kirtan sessions. You are learning Hindustani classical music specifically. You prefer a single specialized tool over a versatile one. You want the specific sustained reed tone that is part of Indian musical culture. You are committed to specifically Indian music contexts.</p>

      <h2>Choose Keyboard If</h2>
      <p>You want to learn both Indian and Western music. You have very limited budget (basic keyboards start at Rs 2000 vs Rs 5000+ for harmonium). You want built-in learning features like lesson modes and rhythmic accompaniment. You need a completely silent practice option with headphones. You plan to compose or produce music digitally. You want one instrument that covers everything.</p>

      <h2>Why Harmonium for Indian Music</h2>
      <p>For pure Indian music learning harmonium has clear advantages. The physical act of pumping bellows develops breath awareness that transfers to singing. The limited range focuses learning on what matters for Indian music. The sustained drone capability is essential for raga practice. The authentic tone aligns with what students hear in Indian musical contexts. You learn harmonium specifically — not a generalized keyboard.</p>

      <h2>Our Recommendation</h2>
      <p>If your primary goal is Indian music — bhajans, kirtan, classical accompaniment — start with harmonium. Use our free web harmonium first to confirm your interest before buying a physical instrument. If you want both Indian and Western or need versatility start with a keyboard. Many serious Indian music students eventually own both — keyboard for composing and practice at home, harmonium for performance and accompaniment.</p>

